ss_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume focuses on the role of language in the construction of knowledge about HIV/AIDS in diverse regions of the world. The collection of studies yields helpful insights about the discursive construction of this knowledge in both formal and informal contexts, while demonstrating how the tools of applied linguistics can be exercised to reveal a deeper understanding of the production and dissemination of this knowledge. The authors use a range of qualitative methodologies to critically explore the role of language and discourse in educational contexts in which various and sometimes competing forms of knowledge about HIV/AIDS are constructed. They draw on various forms of discourse analysis, ethnography, and social semiotics to interpret meaning-making practices in HIV/AIDS education in Australia, Cambodia, Burkina Faso, Hong Kong, India, South Africa, Tanzania, Thailand, and Uganda.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAIDS (Disease)xPreventionvCross-cultural studies. 0aAIDS (Disease)xPreventionxStudy and teaching. 0aApplied linguistics. 0aHIV infectionsxPreventionvCross-cultural studies. 0aHIV infectionsxPreventionxStudy and teaching. 0aLanguage and languages. 0aLanguage and medicine. 0aSociolinguistics. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aCommunication studies.  aDiscourse analysis.  aEthnography.  aHIV/AIDS discourses.  aHIV/AIDS education .  aHIV/AIDS prevention.  aHealth literacies.  aSocial semiotics .1 aButhelezi, Thabisile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemente, Ángeles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrescher, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinn, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc